# =============================================================================
# bluecat - network install Kickstart (TEMPLATE)
# =============================================================================
# This is a TEMPLATE. `mise build:iso` renders it into iso/bluecat.ks by
# substituting the @@...@@ placeholders (registry / image / tag), then embeds
# the result into a small Fedora boot ISO with `mkksiso`.
#
# Why Anaconda + Kickstart instead of bootc-image-builder (bib):
#   bib derives its build recipe from the os-release ID field and only knows
#   fedora/centos/rhel. Our image is rebranded to ID="bluecat", so bib fails
#   with "could not find def file for distro bluecat-44". Anaconda's
#   `ostreecontainer` does NOT care about ID - it just pulls the container -
#   so this keeps ID="bluecat" fully intact.
#
# The installer does NOT carry the OS payload; `ostreecontainer` pulls the
# bootc image straight from the registry over the network at install time.
# That keeps this ISO small and valid across image changes: whatever is
# currently pushed under the configured tag is what gets installed.
#
# This Kickstart is intentionally MINIMAL: it only activates networking (needed
# for the registry pull) and points ostreecontainer at the image. Everything
# else - keyboard, language/region, timezone, users, partitioning and LUKS2
# encryption - is left to the interactive graphical installer, so the user
# decides as much as possible.
#
# REQUIREMENT: the target image must already be pushed and the registry must be
# reachable at install time.
# =============================================================================

# Graphical installer, fully interactive: we deliberately DO NOT pre-answer
# keyboard layout, language/region, timezone, users or partitioning. Anaconda
# will prompt for all of them, so the person installing chooses everything -
# including the partition scheme and whether to enable LUKS2 disk encryption.
graphical

# Bring up networking - this is the ONE thing we must set, because
# `ostreecontainer` below fetches the image from the registry over the network.
# It does not lock anything down: the user can still change network settings in
# the installer.
network --bootproto=dhcp --device=link --activate --onboot=on

# The actual network install of the bootc image.
#   --url          : the OCI image reference (registry/name:tag), rendered by
#                    the task from IMAGE_REGISTRY / IMAGE_NAME / ISO_IMAGE_TAG
#   --transport    : pull straight from an OCI registry
#   --no-signature-verification : we rely on TLS transport security only; the
#                    images are not ostree/sigstore signed yet. Harden later by
#                    signing on push and configuring a policy here.
ostreecontainer --url=@@IMAGE_REF@@ --transport=registry --no-signature-verification --stateroot=bluecat

# The boot splash and LUKS prompt are rendered from the initramfs. Regenerate it
# through rpm-ostree against the installed sysroot so first boot uses the bluecat
# Plymouth assets without bypassing ostree/bootc's initramfs integration.
%post --nochroot --erroronfail --log=/mnt/sysimage/root/bluecat-initramfs.log
rpm-ostree --sysroot=/mnt/sysimage initramfs --enable
%end

# Reboot and eject the media when the install finishes.
reboot --eject
